-- BHP, Healthscope, Orica, Rio, Virgin, Woodside: Australian Stock Preview
-- Shani Raja
-- 2010-07-15T22:16:18Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-15/bhp-healthscope-orica-rio-virgin-woodside-australian-stock-preview.html

          
          
             The following is a list of companies
whose shares may rise or fall in Australia. This preview
includes news announced after markets closed yesterday. All
prices are from yesterday’s close unless otherwise stated.  
 The S&P/ASX 200 Index  futures contract  due in September
declined 0.2 percent to 4,425 as of 6:59 a.m. in Sydney. The
 Bank of New York Australia ADR Index  rose 0.2 percent. The
 S&P/ASX 200 Index  fell 0.4 percent to 4,442.60.  
 Mining shares: Copper futures for September delivery rose
0.1 percent to $3.012 a pound in New York.  
 BHP Billiton  (BHP AU), the world’s largest mining company,
slipped 0.7 percent to A$38.13 in Sydney. Its American
depositary receipts increased 0.5 percent in New York trading.  
 Rio Tinto Group  (RIO AU), the world’s third-largest mining
company, decreased 1.1 percent to A$66.61 in Sydney.  
 Baosteel Group Corp., China’s second-largest steelmaker,
said yesterday iron-ore producers should reconsider how they
price the raw material as prices slide.  
 Oil companies: Crude for August delivery dropped 0.6
percent to settle at $76.62 a barrel on the New York Mercantile
Exchange.  
 Woodside Petroleum Ltd.  (WPL AU), Australia’s second-
largest oil and gas producer, dropped 0.4 percent to A$42.85.
Rival  Santos Ltd.  (STO AU) fell 1 percent to A$13.77.  
 Gold producers: Gold futures for August delivery increased
0.1 percent to $1,208.30 in New York.  
 Newcrest Mining Ltd.  (NCM AU), Australia’s biggest gold
producer declined 0.7 percent to A$35.02.  
 Healthscope Ltd.  (HSP AU): TPG Capital and the Carlyle
Group are likely to vie against Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. to
win Healthscope with bids for the company to close today, the
Australian Financial Review reported in its Street Talk column.
Australia’s second-largest hospital operator dropped 0.9 percent
to A$5.41.  
 Oceania Capital Partners Ltd.  (OCP AU): The investment
company wants to sell its Signature Security Group unit, the
Australian Financial Review reported in its Street Talk column,
without saying where it got the information. Oceania decreased
1.3 percent to A$1.53.  
 Orica Ltd. : (ORI AU): The world’s largest industrial
explosives maker was downgraded to “neutral” from
“outperform” at Credit Suisse Group AG by equity analyst  Rohan Gallagher . Orica rose 1.7 percent to A$24.92.  
 Qantas Airways Ltd.  (QAN AU): Aircraft refuelers at Sydney
airport plan to strike for 24 hours on July 21 over a pay
dispute, the Australian Financial Review reported, citing the
Transport Workers Union. Qantas fell 0.9 percent to A$2.30.  
 Virgin Blue Holdings Ltd.  (VBA AU): Air New Zealand Ltd.,
the nation’s largest carrier, denied a report it has bought a
stake in Virgin Blue as the two airlines await a ruling on a
proposed alliance. Australia’s second-largest airline was
unchanged at 31.5 Australian cents.  
